name: Ragnar Trail Tetons - WY
intro: Ragnar Trail Tetons-WY presented by Salomon is the overnight trail running relay you've been waiting for! Brand new for 2016, this venue is situated at Grand Targhee Ski Resort and features arguably one of the most spectacular views in North America of the Grand Tetons. Teams of 8 (or 4) will come together in early September for a weekend of challenging trail running and unforgettable camping. Teams run relay style on the green, yellow and red loops on trails that carve and weave through the forest and to the top of Grand Targhee. The trails are tough and fun - just like the Ragnarians who come to conquer them. Back at Ragnar Village, you'll roast s'mores, meet other runners and soak up the party vibe under 1 billion stars overhead. Everything about this race screams adventure including your lungs, yeah your lungs might be screaming too. Mark your trail running calendar: September 9-10. See you in the Tetons!
home: Ragnar Trail Tetons-WY presented by Salomon is the overnight trail running relay you’ve been waiting for! Brand new for 2016, this venue is situated at Grand Targhee Ski Resort and features arguably one of the most spectacular views in North America of the Grand Tetons. Teams of 8 (or 4) will come together in early September for a weekend of challenging trail running and unforgettable camping. Teams run relay style on the “green,” “yellow” and “red” loops on trails that carve and weave through the forest and to the top of Grand Targhee. The trails are tough and fun - just like the Ragnarians who come to conquer them. Back at Ragnar Village, you’ll roast s’mores, meet other runners and soak up the party vibe under 1 billion stars overhead. Everything about this race screams adventure… including your lungs, yeah… your lungs might be screaming too. Mark your trail running calendar: September 9-10. See you in the Tetons!
village:
Ragnar Village is the heart and soul of the event. Each trail begins and ends in Ragnar Village. It is the start line, the finish line, and the exchange point. After each loop you will return to the support of your teammates and the adulation of the teams around you. Ragnar Village will be complete with:

    • Bonfire

    • Food & snacks (Friday night pasta dinner included for each runner)

    • Movies

    • S’mores, Coffee, & Hot Cocoa                                                                      

    • Music

    • Billions of stars
 

Ragnar Village is located at Grand Targhee Resort: 3300 Ski Hill Road, Alta, WY 83414. 

 

Team Campsite

Each team will be given a location to set up their team campsite in the Ragnar Village. Camping is FREE to runners, family, friends, and crew on Friday night. Camping Thursday or Friday night is $20 per site collected by Grand Targhee. Or if you don’t feel like roughing there is Grand Targhee has lodging available.  For more information on your team’s campsite please see the Plan Your Trip page. 
 

Partners

Salomon - Demo a pair of Salomon shoes out on a loop

REI - Night writing. Coffee barista will be giving instructions for the perfect brew! 

High West Whiskey - Sample High West around the campfire! 21+ only. 

Goal Zero - Get charged up! Free charging station for your electronic devices

Nathan - Get your photo taken with the What Color is Your Pee Banner! Nathan products for purchase as well.

Bondi Band - Stop by the Bondi Band booth to purchase your moisture wicking headbands, armbands, and other must have running accessories.

Elevated Legs - Pneumatic compression leg sleeves will help with your recovery. Come get your legs squeezed at the Elevated Legs tent.

BEX - Stop by the BEX booth to play a fun basketball game for prizes

CEP Compression - Selling compression items for all your needs

Addaday - Make sure to "borrow" one of our fabulous rollers for the weekend!

Klean Kanteen - Our official Sustainability partner providing you with water for the weekend

 

 

 

Schedule

Training by Salomon

At Salomon our goal is to inspire runners to go beyond the pavement and enjoy greater freedom to run anywhere. We believe that with some tips and training almost anyone can become a trail runner and run the Ragnar Trail Relay. We are here to guide you on your training journey as you prepare to run the Ragnar Trail Relay.

charity:
Tetons is just around the corner. Make the weekend even more meaningful by fundraising for a Ragnar charity partner or your favorite charity on everydayhero, the official fundraising platform of Ragnar Relay Series! 

Simply go here (or click on the everydayhero logo above) and choose your favorite charity – it’s that easy!  Your fundraising page will be created and you can start making every step count.

To date, the Ragnar community has fundraised over 1 million dollars so let's keep it going! 

Questions? Email nonprofits@everydayhero.com.

This Race Release and Waiver (this “Release”) is a contract with legal and binding consequences and it applies to all activities relating to the Event, whether located on the race course, the village or other race-related venues, and also including any camping activity before or after the Event. I have read this Release carefully before signing, and I understand what it means and what I am agreeing to by signing.

I am aware of and appreciate all of these risks. I understand that wild animals, snakes, insects, vehicle traffic and spectators will be present along the race course and that police protection will not be provided. I know that the presence of wild animals and vehicle traffic during the race present certain risks including animal attack and the risk of motor vehicle accidents involving participants, spectators, and/or other vehicles, and that such accidents can result in death or serious injury.

I further understand that the Releasees are not responsible for lost/stolen/damaged items from vehicles or campsites.

  1. As a condition of my participation, I agree to abide by all traffic and pedestrian laws and regulations and to follow any and all of Releasees’ safety instructions, including all rules and conditions set forth in the Trail Guide, which is available on the Ragnar Relay Series website, www.ragnarrelay.com.. I understand that my failure to do so may result in serious injury or death and may be grounds for my disqualification from this Event.
  2. I acknowledge that I should not enter and participate in this event unless I am medically able and properly trained. I agree to abide by any decision of a race official relative to my ability to safely complete this trail race and I further agree that race officials may authorize necessary emergency treatment for me.
  3. I represent and warrant that (a) my team and I will participate fully in all of the safety training provided by the Ragnar Relay Series, and (b) they and I agree to adhere to the rules and regulations included in such safety training.
  4. Having read this waiver and knowing and assuming these risks, and in consideration of the acceptance of my participation, I hereby for myself, my heirs, my executors, administrators or anyone else who might claim on my behalf (collectively my “Successors”), covenant not to sue, and FOREVER WAIVE, RELEASE, DISCHARGE, and HOLD HARMLESS Releasees from any and all claims, injuries, damages, liabilities, causes of action, and expenses (including without limitation attorney’s fees and costs), and inconvenience to person or property (collectively, “Losses”)   of any kind or nature whatsoever arising out of my participation in this Event, even though such liability may arise out of negligence or carelessness on the part of Releasees.
  5. In exchange for my being permitted to participate in the Event, and understanding there will be no additional compensation to me, I hereby authorize Ragnar Events LLC, to use my image or likeness for Event promotional purposes.
  6. I understand the Event registration fees are nonrefundable.  I have read the Trail Guide and agree to abide by the rules and conditions contained therein.
  7. I acknowledge and agree, for myself and my Successors, that the above representations are contractually binding, and that should I or my Successors assert a claim contrary to what I have agreed to in this agreement, the claiming party shall be liable for the expenses (including legal fees) incurred by the Releasees in defending such claim. I consent to the release by any third party to Releasees and their insurance carriers of my name and medical information that may relate to any injury or death I may suffer arising from my participation in the Event. meta_description: Ragnar Trail Tetons-WY presented by Salomon is the overnight trail running relay you've been waiting for! Brand new for 2016, this venue is situated at Grand Targhee Ski Resort and features arguably one of the most spectacular views in North America of the Grand Tetons.

legs.name: Green Loop - Jolly Green Giants Trail
legs.description: The Green Loop leaves the Village running along the parking area with nice views of the camping area. A quick right after safely crossing the road puts you onto single track. You barrel down a nice section of buffed out trail through the trees. At a half mile the trail spills into a broad meadow as you start a slow climb to a bald hill with a great view of nearly the entire course as well as Teton Valley below. On a clear night, the stars will be spectacular and the headlamps bobbing along through the trees below and on the ridgelines above will give glimpses of what’s in store for you. Then, it’s back into the trees on plush single-track with just the right decline. This might be your fastest mile ever. Near mile two the trail hits a few switchbacks as you skirt the edge of the camping field, the laughs (and maybe a few snores) from your fellow racers at camp trickle through the trees. A right turn just before mile three merges you with the Yellow and Red Loops and brings you back home.

legs.name: Yellow Loop - Buffalo Soldier Trail
legs.description: The Yellow Loop is a nice cruiser, the uphill stretches are never as long as your mind might tell you and they are quickly broken up by flats or downhills. Go ahead, push yourself and run it out. You leave the Village running past the base area. At this point you have a few hundred feet of dirt road before a right turn puts you on a great single-track. This is where the fun starts in earnest. The trail heads up a draw and before mile one crosses a stream to start a short climb up and out of the gulley. When the trail turns a corner, the views open up and you start to cut across a contour of ski runs. You can imagine how much fun it would be to shred downhill here in a few months. The next mile is fast with wide open views of some killer ski terrain that until recently was cat access only. Just after mile two you go back into the tress and tackle some short switchback climbs. Just get ready, around mile three you come around a corner, and if it is clear, you will be granted a spectacular view of The Grand and Middle Teton. Not to mention the trail in this section will have a smile plastered to your face. Near mile 4 you jump onto a dirt road for a steady half mile climb and then a left turn puts you on a GNARLY downhill mountain bike single-track. Be careful here, there are some steep drops and rock ledges. It is not your grandmother’s trail but you mountain goats out there you will be in heaven. After half a mile of the grin and bear it section, the single-track joins the Red Loop on a dirt road for the final dash. From here you loop around the main base area, join with the Green Loop, and race back to the Village.

legs.name: Red Loop - Grand View Trail
legs.description: The view from the top of The Red is A-M-A-ZING! Problem is…you have to get there first, and we’re not going to lie, you have to earn it. Red leaves the Village with yellow and take a right onto the single track. This is where things start to get hard. For the next mile, the trail surface is buffed out single-track and the cut crosses ski runs as it climbs north across the resort, passing near the recently removed  Blackfoot lift. At mile two, the trail turns to climb up a rocky ridge and this is where things get really hard. A look down to the right will give you a view of the Village and Green Loop below and Teton Valley beyond. A look left will find the terrain dropping away from a sheer rock cliff with the Tetons looming in the distance. Straight ahead, a mean ridgeline, yes, that is where you are going. At mile three the trail turns to a cat-track dirt road and you get a momentary relief from the climb…momentary, as you push on, climbing again towards the summit of Fred’s Mountain. Once you get to the top of Dreamcatcher chair you know you are steps away from one of the most spectacular views on the continent. Most people take a chair lift for what you just earned, not you, although you may be wish you had. A short little loop to the true summit provides you with what you came here for, a truly Grand view. And then, it is all downhill. Back down the dirt road of your final approach and then a left to continue your bomb downhill for a mile. This is where you can turn your brain off and recover you lungs and turn loose. Then, at mile 5, a left turn takes you off of the dirt road and back onto a sick single-track for nearly a mile. This section is a bit bi-polar, alternating from a soft plush ribbon of single-track to jagged rocky technical trail. All of it, however, is amazingly beautiful. Green grass, colorful wildflowers, black rock cliffs, and the picturesque Teton Valley below. Just before mile 6 you turn right onto a dirt road for the final stretch. You did it. You conquered the hardest loop in Ragnar Trail history!

reg_system.name: Ragnar Trail Tetons - WY
reg_system.description: If you are looking to be brought to tears over beauty (and maybe also because of the challenge) look no further. Arguably one of the most spectacular views in North America, the Tetons have been a sight to be held, even long before those lonely French trappers took the liberty of naming them. Not to mention the amazing single-track the folks at Grand Targhee Resort have built. You aren’t supposed to name favorites, but of the entire series, we may have to make an exception here. Come join us out west for a weekend of camping (or hotel & hot tub), trail running, and friends. Everything about this race screams adventure… including your lungs, yeah… your lungs might be screaming too.
